# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET 5+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone** — no equivalent needed
3. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be raised** by the runtime

## Modern .NET 8 Implementation

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask Stop(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful completion up to timeout
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)))
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log warning; task is abandoned
            // In .NET 8 there is NO way to forcibly kill a thread safely
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has no `Thread.Abort` equivalent. You *must* make blocking calls cancellation-aware (accept `CancellationToken`). |
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()`** | If this wraps a synchronous blocking call (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take`), use `.Take(token)` or switch to `Channel<T>.ReadAsync(token)`. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` gone** | Simply remove it — `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception, no special reset needed. |
| **`volatile bool` flag** | Replace with `CancellationToken` — it's thread-safe, composable, and integrates with async APIs. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` for shutdown** | Replace with `Task.WhenAny` + timeout — non-blocking and deterministic. |
| **Resource cleanup** | Implement `IAsyncDisposable` so DI containers and `await using` handle lifetime correctly. |

## If You Can't Make the Work Async

For purely synchronous workloads that can't accept a token:

```csharp
private void ProcessLoopSync(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(); // still blocking
        if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        ProcessItem(item);
    }
    FlushBuffers();
}
```

> ⚠️ This only checks cancellation *between* items. If `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely, the worker won't stop. The real fix is making it accept a `CancellationToken`.

## For ASP.NET / Hosted Services

If this runs inside a web app, use `BackgroundService`:

```csharp
public class MyProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
// Register: builder.Services.AddHostedService<MyProcessor>();
```

This gives you graceful shutdown integration with the host for free.
